To check if an HTML element is not empty in JavaScript, you can compare the element's `innerHTML` or `textContent` properties to the empty string. Here are examples of how to do this for various HTML elements:

```javascript
// For a div element with id "myDiv"
if (document.getElementById("myDiv").innerHTML !== "") {
  console.log("Div element is not empty.");
} else {
  console.log("Div element is empty.");
}

// For a paragraph element with class "myParagraph"
if (document.querySelector(".myParagraph").textContent.trim() !== "") {
  console.log("Paragraph element is not empty.");
} else {
  console.log("Paragraph element is empty.");
}
```

In both examples, the `innerHTML` and `textContent` properties are used to retrieve the content within the respective HTML elements. The `trim()` method is used in the second example to remove any leading or trailing whitespace from the `textContent` string. The `!==` operator is used to compare the content of the elements to the empty string, checking if they are not equal. If the condition is met, the program outputs "Div element is not empty" or "Paragraph element is not empty," indicating that the respective HTML element is not empty.
